# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wasi-interface
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] An **application binary interface** (**ABI**) is an interface exposed by software that is defined for in-process machine code access.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Often, the exposing software is a library, and the consumer is a program.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] An ABI is at a relatively low level of abstraction.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Interface compatibility depends on the target hardware and the software build toolchain.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] In contrast, an application programming interface (API) defines access in source code, which is a relatively high-level, hardware-independent, and human-readable format.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] An API defines an interface at the source code level, before compilation, whereas an ABI defines an interface to compiled code.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] API compatibility is generally the concern for system design and of the toolchain.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] However, a programmer may have to deal with an ABI directly when writing a program in multiple languages or when using multiple compilers for the same language.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] A complete ABI enables a program that supports an ABI to run without modification on multiple operating systems that provide the ABI.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] The target system must provide any required libraries (that implement the ABI), and there may be other prerequisites.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] ABIs include the Intel Binary Compatibility Standard (iBCS) and the System V Release 4 ABIs for various instruction sets.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] An **embedded ABI** (**EABI**), used on an embedded operating system, specifies aspects such as file formats, data types, register usage, stack frame organization, and function parameter passing of an embedded software program.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Each compiler and assembler that supports an EABI creates object code that is compatible with code generated by other such compilers and assemblers.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] This allows developers to link libraries generated by one compiler with object code generated by another.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Typically, an EABI is optimized for performance for the limited resources of the target embedded system.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Therefore, an EABI may omit abstractions between kernel and user space typically found in desktop operating systems.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] The choice of EABI can affect performance.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Widely used EABIs include the PowerPC, Arm, and MIPS EABIs.
[src:wasi-interface/application-binary-interface] Specific software implementations like the C library may impose additional limitations to form more concrete ABIs; one example is the GNU OABI and EABI for ARM, both of which are subsets of the ARM EABI.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The **Portable Operating System Interface** (**POSIX**; IPA: /ˈpɒz.ɪks/) is a family of standards specified by the IEEE Computer Society for maintaining compatibility between operating systems.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] In order to define a level of compatibility, POSIX specifies many aspects of functionality that can be classified as application programming interface (API), command-line shell, and shell commands.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Originally derived from commonly-found Unix APIs, shells, and commands (partly because Unix was considered manufacturer-neutral), today many systems conform to the standard – including branded Unix systems, Unix-like systems, and many systems that were historically unrelated to Unix.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The standardized user command line and scripting interface were based on the UNIX System V Bourne shell.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Many user-level programs, services, and utilities (including awk, echo, ed) were also standardized, based on UNIX System V versions of them, along with required program-level services (including basic I/O: file, terminal, and network).
[src:wasi-interface/posix] POSIX also defines a standard threading library API which is supported by most modern operating systems.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The POSIX standard is developed by the Austin Group (a joint working group among the IEEE, The Open Group, and the ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22/WG 15).
[src:wasi-interface/posix] POSIX is intended to be used by both application and system developers.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The standards emerged from a project that began in 1984 building on work from related activity in the */usr/group* association.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Richard Stallman suggested the name *POSIX* to the IEEE instead of the former *IEEE-IX*.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The committee found it more easily pronounceable and memorable, and thus adopted it.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Originally, POSIX referred to IEEE Std 1003.1-1988, released in 1988.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The family of POSIX standards is formally designated as **IEEE 1003** and the ISO/IEC standard number is ISO/IEC 9945.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] POSIX originally consisted of a single document for core services but over time additional documents were published to extend and revise the specification.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Before 1997, POSIX comprised multiple documents that were published over the course of several years.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] After 1997, the Austin Group produces specifications titled Single UNIX Specification (SUS).
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Over time, the group publishes versions of this specification and later POSIX is amended per some or all of a SUS version.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] A SUS version consists of a collection of volumes – each for a grouping of required behavior – plus other information (outside of a volume).
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Each volume is assigned an issue number that is the same for each volume of a version, but is not the same value as the version.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] For example, SUS version 3 (SUSv3) includes volumes labeled issue 6.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] IEEE Std 1003.1-2004 modifies POSIX.1-2001 via two minor updates or errata referred to as technical corrigenda documents.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Similar to its predecessor, POSIX.1-2008 (*IEEE Std 1003.1-2008*, 2016 Edition) consists of most of the normative material of SUSv4 (issue 7 of volumes *Base Definitions*, *System Interfaces and Headers*, *Commands and Utilities*).
[src:wasi-interface/posix] SUSv4 also includes rationale information that largely applies to POSIX although not included per se.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] As of POSIX 2024, the standard is aligned with the C17 language standard.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] POSIX mandates 512-byte default block sizes for the df and du utilities, reflecting the typical size of blocks on disks.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] When Richard Stallman and the GNU team were implementing POSIX for the GNU operating system, they objected to this on the grounds that most people think in terms of 1024 byte (or 1 KiB) blocks.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The environment variable POSIX_ME_HARDER was introduced to allow the user to force the standards-compliant behaviour.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The variable name was later changed to POSIXLY_CORRECT.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] As of 2025, this variable is also used for a number of other behaviour quirks.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] An operating system can be classified depending upon the degree of conformance with a POSIX standard.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Current versions of the following operating systems have been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests and their certification has not expired and the operating system has not been discontinued.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Some versions of the following operating systems had been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The certification has expired and some of the operating systems have been discontinued.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The following operating systems are not certified as POSIX conformant, but they conform in large part to the standard by implementing POSIX support via a compatibility feature (usually translation libraries, or a layer atop the kernel).
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Some technologies allow an operating system to enjoy a level of conformance to POSIX even though the operating system itself has little or no conformance.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] Although Windows does not conform to POSIX, the following technologies provide a level of compliance.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] A lightweight implementation that has POSIX-compatible header files that map POSIX APIs to call their Windows API counterparts.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] An optional Windows subsystem included in Windows NT-based operating systems up to Windows 2000.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] A compatibility layer for running Linux binary executables natively on Windows 10 and 11 using a Linux image such as Ubuntu, Debian, or OpenSUSE among others, acting as an upgrade and replacement for Windows Services for UNIX.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] The first distribution available was Ubuntu.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] From AT&T Research implements a POSIX layer on top of the Win32 APIs.
[src:wasi-interface/posix] although the support remains largely incomplete and not fully interoperable with POSIX-compliant implementations.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:wasi-interface/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:wasi-interface/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] The **WebAssembly System Interface (WASI)** is a group of standards-track API specifications for software compiled to the **W3C WebAssembly (Wasm) standard**.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] WASI is designed to provide a secure standard interface for applications that can be compiled to Wasm from any language, and that may run anywhere, from browsers to clouds to embedded devices.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] By standardizing APIs for WebAssembly, WASI provides a way to compose software written in different languages without costly and clunky interface systems like HTTP-based microservices.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] We believe that every project with a plugin model should be using WASI, and that WASI is ideally suited for projects with SDKs for multiple languages, e.g. client libraries.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] (Sometimes you will see these referred to as Preview 1/2/3 or P1/P2/P3.) WASI 0.3 adds native async support to the Component Model and refactors WASI interfaces to take advantage of async primitives like `stream<T>` and `future<T>`.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] WASI is an open standard under active development by the **WASI Subgroup** in the **W3C WebAssembly Community Group**.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] Discussions happen in GitHub issues, pull requests, and bi-weekly Zoom meetings.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] WASI and Wasm are tools for any type of software developer: whether you're writing web apps, plugins, serverless functions, User-Defined Functions (UDFs) in a database, embedded controller components, sidecar networking filters, or something completely different.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] This site is intended to introduce the concepts and vocabulary of WASI regardless of your background, use-case, or familiarity with the WebAssembly ecosystem.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] There are many different runtimes that support WASI including Wasmtime, WAMR, WasmEdge, wazero, Wasmer, wasmi, wasm3, jco and pywasm.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] Many of these runtimes have different areas of focus (i.e., IoT, embedded devices, and edge for WAMR, server-side and non-web embeddings with components for Wasmtime, and running in JS environments and browsers for Jco).
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] The introductory documentation for each is a great place to start.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] WASI can be implemented by both core Wasm modules and applications built according to the **Component Model**, a specification for Wasm applications that are interoperable and composable.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] You can learn more about components in the Bytecode Alliance's **WebAssembly Component Model** documentation.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] WASI applications run in a **capability-based** sandbox: a Wasm module or component starts with no ambient authority and can only do what the host explicitly grants.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] When you're ready to start building, the Component Model documentation walks through compiling a first component and running it on Wasmtime or jco, with tutorials for Rust, JavaScript, Python, Go, C, C#, and MoonBit.
[src:wasi-interface/wasi-dev] Continue reading to learn more about WASI releases, including available APIs and how they are defined.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:wasi-interface/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
